# .trivyignore — devtools / devtools-dev (context: apps/devtools)
# Added 2026-07-17 after the 2.0.0 rebuild scan (run 29545524010) gated red.
#
# All four findings are ONE false positive, matched four times: trivy's
# node-pkg analyzer reads VS Code's bundled built-in extension manifest
# usr/share/code/resources/app/extensions/npm/package.json — the "npm
# scripts support" UI extension, whose manifest declares name "npm",
# version "1.0.1" (the extension's own version) — and misidentifies it
# as the npm CLI at 1.0.1, then reports every npm-CLI CVE fixed since.
# The npm package manager itself is NOT installed in this image (no
# nodejs/npm apt package; VS Code's `code` deb is the only Node-adjacent
# payload), so there is no vulnerable code to exploit.
#
# Revisit: remove these entries once trivy stops flagging VS Code
# built-in extension manifests as the npm CLI (re-test on a trivy bump
# past 0.72.0), or if a future image change installs a real npm CLI —
# a real npm would be a distro package (ubuntu class), not covered by
# these node-pkg-matched entries, so it would still gate correctly.

# npm CLI < 5.7.1: chown of system paths when npm runs as root. Not the
# npm CLI — VS Code extension manifest misdetection (see header).
CVE-2018-7408

# npm CLI < 6.13.3: `bin` field symlink escape outside node_modules on
# install. No npm CLI in the image; nothing ever runs `npm install`
# with this "package".
CVE-2019-16775

# npm CLI < 6.13.3: arbitrary file write via crafted `bin` entry on
# install. Same misdetected extension manifest, same reasoning.
CVE-2019-16776

# npm CLI < 6.13.4: global node_modules binary overwrite on install.
# Same misdetected extension manifest, same reasoning.
CVE-2019-16777
